I'm really grateful for all the help she's given me because I definitely wouldn't have been able to get through this whole college application thing without her support and guidance.

I'd appreciate some more specific advice on how to start the introduction in a way that sounds natural, as well as some insight into how the current sections of my essay flow and form a narrative in totality.

The changes to my description of the extracurricular itself make reading my essay a much more vivid, personal experience. I also appreciate the in-line suggestions and revisions!

The edits--especially for the introductory sentences--really go a long way in making my essay more authentically me. I think adding this small bit of humor will go a long way towards making this essay more impactful.

The essays simply made the essay significantly more personable! I think that the phrasing make much more sense now, although there are two edits in particular that I plan on revising myself. I feel like this essay is starting to capture more and more of who I am with every revision!

I spent hours brainstorming how to make this essay as interesting as possible. Initially I fell into the pitfall of writing a reserach summary and not a college essay, and Lance's feedback--especially in regards to my introduction and the explosion motif I have--helped a lot!

I think some of the suggestions make the roommate essay sound almost too reflective and somewhat undermine the tone of the essay. In my opinion, some of the cuts make the essay read less naturally. Regardles,s the edits themselves added a lot of much-needed personality to this essay, so I'm very happy!

The edits made the essay appear extremely naturally and calmly written (for lack of a better word), which provides a very human contrast to the more serious tone that some of my other essays had to adopt due to their content.

Bach and Beethoven taught me two languages – music and German. For me, the study of classical arts isn’t isolated, but is a reflection of the history, society, and people who gave them life.
 

 With a Harvard education, I’ll have the means to redefine the role of the arts in society. I’ll continue expanding access to music, using it as a language to relate important works to our lives. I will work to create meaningful educational programs that promote critical thinking, historical understanding, and emotional balance.
 

 My aspirations will require studies in German, Music, History and beyond, taking classes like The Politics of Cultural Production and The Role of Music in Health and Education. At the CES and Sound Lab, I’ll experiment and hone research skills. Just as I once experienced my first opera, I’ll open doors for others to explore the music and culture within, one note at a time.

The review was detailed, precise, and carefully done—it was truly worth the time I waited for it.

 One small thing I’d prefer next time is slightly stricter guidance to help refine my work even more—for example, direct notes like ‘try to replace this activity with a better one’ or ‘this isn’t helping your application.’ Feedback like this would be incredibly valuable. I understand you may not have noticed such cases in my list, but that’s exactly the type of reviewing and editing I find most helpful, since it avoids wasting time on weaker points when we can rewrite something stronger. 
 Thank you again for the effort and care you put into this review—it really helps me grow:))

I really want to thank Katherine for putting so much effort into this review. Her inline edits were super careful and really improved the flow and transitions of my essay. I also loved how detailed and thoughtful her feedback was—it gave me clear, actionable suggestions while still letting my own voice shine through. I’m especially grateful because she supported me in writing about this topic, which really means a lot to me!

Hunter’s feedback felt sensational because he was both supportive and precise. He showed me how tiny edits, like changing “I smiled” to “I forced a smile” or “searched” to “scoured forums,” can reshape the whole arc. The care he put into inline comments and details made me feel guided, and it’s making a huge difference in how my story flows.

Hunter didn’t just suggest edits, he helped me see how the essay could flow more naturally and connect more deeply with Swarthmore’s values. The way he focused on rhythm, precision, and tying the “building” motif to diversity and dialogue made everything click. I also really appreciated how personal and supportive his tone was; it felt like guidance from someone who truly cared about helping the story reach its full potential.
Thanks so much for the detailed feedback—it really clarified where to focus. I saw you shared a revised version; do you think this new draft has the potential to move past a 7 with more refinement?

Overall the review gave me motivation to continue editing and gave me a good idea of the direction that my revisions need to go!

The line edits are quite heavy so thus take away from my writing style (e.g. instead of just saying "this is a run-on sentence, so I think you should split this up," they actually do that work for me and rewrite my sentences), and I don't think the suggested edits reduce the word count either. While I appreciate the feedback on adding more concrete details, I was put off by the notes on my book selection. In my essay, I refered to "sharing my love for classics," and while I acknowledge that it's a deviation from the rest of my essay and thus might be misleading, I think my activities list (which was provided) makes it clear that two of biggest interests are Latin (i.e. CLASSICS) and computer science. I think the part that most put me off, however, was the list of five books that they suggested I can use to replace the book I discussed in my essay. Not only does it appear AI-generated to me, but it would also be a lie if I were to claim in my essay that I read a book I didn't actually read. I appreciate the thought, but sometimes metaphorical connections in life aren't always perfect, and I think that's okay.

Hi, this is Angela’s father. Angela’s essay is very authentic because it reflects her true voice and personal experiences. For example, the opening question comes directly from a real discussion she had during her robotics summer program, so it should not be changed to reference AI. In addition, the academic threads she mentions are officially listed within Georgia Tech’s Computer Engineering major and align perfectly with her background and interests. I don’t think it would be a good idea to shift the focus to pure cybersecurity. Many of the specific details in her essay come from her own experiences, reflections, and thorough research on Georgia Tech. I believe that good essay editing should preserve her authentic voice, stay true to her background, and demonstrate understanding of the colleges she is writing about.

column10: This criticism only elicits fatigue. This a second round of edits, a draft following implementation of all original revisions - the impossible standards of your rating system are frankly unrealistic (compared with publicly released Essays that Worked) and only serve to create distance between yourself and the customer. Maybe consider knocking off the top rating (reserving that for "off the charts"), as it is literally impossible to write a perfect essay with inherently subjective judging. Being just slightly more generous with the rating doesn't create false hope, or reduce demand for your services - it's literally just more reflective of the real admissions process, where there's no "9/9" essay.

If I am being honest, the cleaned version sounds like AI. Mr. Ornburn is my calculus teacher, but he got confused for my physics teacher. The negation structure that is repeated in the cleaned version is the main reason that it sounds like AI -- "It wasn't just math; it was the language of the universe". Language of the universe also sounds AI generated. The negation structure continues throughout the cleaned version with lines such as "even the sharks wasn't just swimming by" and "I wasn't just swimming". Phrasing like "Too easy" sounds a bit off putting, as if I feel like I am better than the curriculum? I want it to just sound like curiosity, not arrogance. I also miss the specifcity from the entire problem; this was a differential equations problem over the integration factors, so I wish that specifcity was there. Also, the detail that I started calculus cafe was taken out, and the last sentence with sweeping generalizations like the "world is an equation to be solved" also feels like AI. The last feedback I got from Vy was strong, espcailly with the numbered points that gave me clear direction on what I can do. I would appreciate clear, numbered feedback (like my last edit) and a cleaned version the preserves my voice (making surgical edits rather than redoing the whole story) + doesn't sound like AI. Thank you for your time :)

I’m a bit confused by the feedback I’ve been receiving and wanted to clarify what would be most helpful for me moving forward.
 

 My first editor encouraged me to remove specificity from the opening paragraph (for example, the Zoe and Hiroshi details in the first edit), while the second round of feedback suggests reintroducing specificity through examples like Jasmine and Jason. That contradiction makes it difficult for me to understand the intended direction.
 

 Additionally, I’m finding that there are many suggestions about how to revise rather than a decisive, integrated revision itself. What would help me most is a clean, elevated draft where the edits are already implemented.
 

 Ideally, I’d love to see a strong example draft—even if some details are hypothetical. If you could clearly highlight which parts are placeholders or made up, I can then replace them with accurate, personal details. Seeing the piece fully realized would help me understand what an elevated version looks like as a whole, rather than trying to assemble it from suggestions.
 

 Thanks so much for your patience and understanding. I know you guys have a lot of essays coming through right now, so please don't take the feedback personally; I am just letting you guys know what works for me, as I will be using this service alot in the coming days. Once again, thank you for your support and effort!

The feedback you provided goes straight to the heart of the essay, allowing us to step back and see the bigger picture of what a personal statement should truly achieve. column10: First, my editor affirmed by glows that I worried might not have been clear to some readers. She understood my genuine curiosity and praised my personality and voice sprinkled throughout the essay. Then, she told me to bring up facts and dive deeper into one or two moments longer to show the reader I truly learned something. I was originally going to do this, but totally forgot, so thankful that she noticed it. Her feedback regarding expanding the grandmother's story, an essential part of the plot, elevated the part's importance in my eyes as I was overlooking it as a minor paragraph before the conclusion. She told me to refine my conclusion for a much deeper takeaway for the reader. Lastly, the outline she left me with blanks to insert my voice will save me a lot of time. With all this feedback, I am now confident my essay will stand out uniquely and reveal my background and personality with anecdotes, humor, and introspective thoughts. Thank you Karen for all your feedback and Elevated for building this essay editing platform that transforms mundane essays into gems.

column10:
What made it sensational:
 

 The feedback directly addressed my concerns about my essay not being cohesive as originally it suddenly switches themes in the middle. The feedback showed how to fix this and stick to the theme. The reflection letter also confirmed my thoughts about the lack of focus on one theme. It also gave me other good advice as well. Furthermore, I really appreciated how Serena was able to cut down the word count significantly as I struggled with that greatly.
 

 What could've been done better/things I'm confused about:
 

 In the comment section of the portal, I included a question about whether I should include pushback from the parents of my students regarding my teaching style to add conflict to the essay. I think Serena may have not understood it (since I was limited with word count in the comment box and I had to abbreviate) so she might've skipped it. One thing I would like to see in the future is have the comment box word limit expanded as I want insight on the concerns I have about the essay as well. I would've also liked it if she answered the other question above that one about Hindu terms being confusing. As for the rest of the questions, she pretty much indirectly answered all of them in her reflection letter so that was fantastic.
 

 In the comment box, I requested moderate focus on structural edits. In the feedback, it says that my essay didn't need too many structural edits. I honestly didn't think my original essay was that good, so I was kind of surprised to hear that (I thought I did a good job storytelling but it lacked cohesion and hence I thought structural edits were needed). So, does this imply that with the current clean draft she provided, I could take the essay to a 8/9 or even 9/9 level? Originally I thought that in order to get to that level I would need structural edits (since polish can only get you so far, right?), but I was just a little confused when it said I didn't need any. In the reflection letter it talks about adding some simple sentences which can go a long way. Are these the types of things that would take my essay to that level? Maybe my understanding will change after I look at the rubric, but right now the link is not clickable. (NOTE: not really anything inherently bad here, but just made me a little confused). 
 

 Lastly, I feel like in certain areas in the clean draft, like the conclusion paragraph, the writing felt a little flat/generic (e.g. "Through this experience, I have learned that..."). In my comments I requested edits/advice to give it more "pop" because I thought my original essay sounded kind of boring to read.
 

 Final Thoughts:
 

 Taken as whole, the feedback is still very SENSATIONAL. Though I wrote much more about the negatives than the positives above, I still believe overall it was a net positive and I loved seeing this feedback since it was very clear in what I need to do to take my essay to the next level.

The feedback and reflection letter provided clear pointers on how to make the essay more focused on how I impacted the community and how the community impacted me. Furthermore it explained how to make my contributions seem less passive. It also told me how to fix the loose ends (like how I randomly named a statistic in the beginning), which was helpful. Some of the feedback I kind of expected (like the one about the statistic), but others were things I didn't realize I needed to fix. I really liked that they were presented in a very clear manner.
 

 When submitting this essay, my main goal was to polish the essay with some structural edits if needed. Though the feedback did describe a lot of structural edits I need to make (considering the original essay was a 5.5/9), I didn't really see edits on improving its "pop." I'm not entirely sure how to describe pop, but I remember a family friend showed an example of the edits provided for his essay (for the async editing service), and I noticed how the edited version compared to his original copy was far more interesting to read from a literary perspective since there was always something in each paragraph that would kind of catch the reader's attention. In my original essay, I thought it sounded pretty boring to read and I was hoping to see some edits on improving that. It may have been due to the fact that my essay needed major structural edits that the feedback didn't focus much on pop. I think some sample sentences provided in the feedback, although they make the essay clearer and focused on impact, sound a little generic/flat like "I realized that all decisions started with an awareness of the problem..." or "...so that sustainability can become part of their lives" and a couple other places throughout the clean draft. Basically, I wanted help communicating that sense of reciprocal community impact in a more interesting way. Would you say that this is needed in my college essay or any college essay for that matter? Or am I thinking along the wrong lines? Before submitting the essay, I did play with the idea if introducing statistics about impact, but I thought it would sound like a resume dump if I did so.
 

 In the comment box, I also asked some questions to gain insight on my personal concerns about the essay. I would've liked it if they were directly answered in the feedback (especially the one about whether the montage structure was useful or not). Maybe it was answered in the comments on the side of the document, but I can't see them properly right now in the limited preview mode.
 

 Lastly, I really appreciate the super quick turnaround time. I was surprised when I saw it in my inbox by the time I woke up! Overall, I thought the feedback was great (despite a few parts of it) especially since the feedback on having more clarity in the essay is obviously somewhat more important than "pop"

Hi Julia! 
 First, I want to say a huge thank you for all your help throughout this process. I genuinely couldn't have gotten this far without you. Your feedback has pushed me to dig deeper, find my voice, and write essays I'm actually proud of. The way you catch things I miss—like threading details, answering prompts directly, and trusting the reader—has made me a better writer.
 I really appreciate how much care you put into every review. It shows, and it matters.
 One small note on the grandmother/Vietnamese coffee essay: I think there may have been a mix-up with the word count. The prompt is actually 100 words maximum, not 200. That's why the essay feels short—I was already at the limit! 
 Would you be able to take another look with the 100-word constraint in mind? I'd love your thoughts on whether it works as is, or if there are small tweaks I can make within that tighter limit.
 Thanks again for everything. Working with you has been such a valuable experience.
 Warmly,
 Man

what the essay meant is for a 250 works duke question below: 
 What is your impression of Duke as a university include that too. (250 word limit)
 

 

 could you pleas do the review and help make it polished for the question above. Let me know if you have any questions.
 

 

 This is what we submitted: 
 

 I live in a household where nothing ever truly dies; it is inevitably “Frankensteined” back to life. With my dad as the mad scientist and me as his apprentice, I spent my childhood piecing together broken items, rather than discarding them. The reliable, albeit eccentric, patchwork tea kettle and tennis ball cosplaying as a doorknob taught me that their strength came from being creative solutions to everyday problems. I hope to bring my love for problem-solving, which unapologetically flourishes outside of conventional boundaries, into every classroom and collaboration at Duke. 
 

  I believe that Duke also values ingenuity at the Trinity College of Arts and Sciences, which I observed firsthand on a tour. As it began to suddenly downpour, the tour guides rerouted with tact, taking us through the underground tunnels connecting the West Union, smiling in the face of obstacles. 
 

  Duke’s Small Group Learning Experience (SGLE) provides spaces for creativity. In the Cognitive Neuroscience and Law seminar, I will encourage the connection of diverse ideas, pulling from a peer’s legal analysis to test against my own understanding of neurobiology. By weaving together different perspectives in tight-knit discussions, I hope to encourage the development of nuanced responses to complex social questions. Beyond the classroom, Duke fosters a culture of ambitious learners who also have the freedom to engage with their passions through advanced research and volunteer opportunities.
 

 I can't wait to join a community of fellow mad scientists, ready to change the world through our own unconventional solutions.

Firstly, I would like to state that the feedback by Dr. Jenny could not have been more clearer and detailed. It feels like she is a doctor of essays! It was more than satisfactory, and the amount and quality of her suggestions were truly sensational. Thank you, Dr. Jenny <3
